SIMPLE: obsess
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: obsess
<hw>ob*sess"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>obsessus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>obsidere</ets> to besiege;
<ets>ob</ets> (see <er>Ob-</er>) + <ets>sedere</ets> to sit.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To besiege; to beset.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir T. Elyot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To excessively preoccupy the thoughts or feelings
of; to haunt the mind persistently.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>obsess</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: obsess
<hw>ob*sess"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be excessively
or persistently preoccupied with something; -- usually used with
<ptcl>on</ptcl> or <ptcl>over</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>obsess</ex> over an
imagined insult</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>At all ages children are driven to figure out what it takes to
succeed among their peers and to give these strategies precedence over
anything their parents foist on them. Weary parents know they are no
match for a child's peers, and rightly <qex>obsess</qex> over the best
neighborhood in which to bring their children up.</q> <rj><qau>Steven
Pinker (How the Mind Works, p. 449-450 [1997]).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>obsessed</ent>⟦br⟧
